{"title_page": "Battle of Hopton Heath", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Battle of Hopton Heath\n| partof      = the [[First English Civil War]]\n| date        = 19 March 1643\n| place       = [[Hopton, Staffordshire|Hopton]], [[Staffordshire]]\n| image       = Battle of Hopton Heath.png\n| image_size  = 250px\n| caption     = ''The Battle of Hopton Heath'', engraved by J. T. Willmore after [[George Cattermole]]\n| result      = Both sides claimed victory\n| combatant1  = {{flagicon image|Royal Standard of England (1603\u20131689).svg|size=22px}} [[Cavalier|Royalists]]\n| combatant2  = [[File:Flag_of_England.svg|22px]] [[Roundhead|Parliamentarians]]\n| commander1  = [[Spencer Compton, 2nd Earl of Northampton]] {{KIA}}\n| commander2  = [[Sir John Gell, 1st Baronet]],<br>\n[[Sir William Brereton, 1st Baronet]]\n| strength1   = '''1,200:''' <br>1,100 cavalry, <br>100 infantry, <br> artillery\n| strength2   = '''1,500:''' <br> infantry, <br> cavalry, <br>15 pieces of artillery\n}}\n{{Campaignbox First English Civil War|state=collapsed}}\nThe '''Battle of Hopton Heath''', in [[Staffordshire]], was a battle of the [[First English Civil War]], fought on Sunday 19 March 1643 between [[Roundhead|Parliamentarian]] forces led by [[Sir John Gell, 1st Baronet]] and [[Sir William Brereton, 1st Baronet|Sir William Brereton]] and a [[Cavalier|Royalist]] force under [[Spencer Compton, 2nd Earl of Northampton]]. The battle ended at nightfall, with the victory remaining a matter of opinion: that the Parliamentarian foot were still in position at nightfall when, as the Royalists themselves admitted, they drew back a little; or that next morning the Royalists occupied the field after the Parliamentarians retreated in the night. The Royalists had captured eight guns, but the Parliamentarians considered their killing of the enemy commander, the Earl of Northampton, of equal significance.\n\n==Background==\nGell had successfully taken the town of [[Lichfield]] in Staffordshire and was on his way with about 1,500 men and some [[artillery]] pieces to join Brereton in a projected attack on the town of [[Stafford]].\n\n==Battle==\nThey met at [[Hopton, Staffordshire|Hopton Heath]] and were attacked there by the Royalists, whose force consisted of about 1,100 cavalry, 100 foot and artillery, including a large artillery piece called Roaring Meg - which must not be confused with the siege mortar \"[[Roaring Meg (cannon)|Roaring Meg]]\" which was cast in 1646 for the siege of Goodrich Castle.\n\nAfter an artillery barrage the Royalist cavalry charged the entrenched Parliamentarians, putting Gell's [[dragoons]] and his and Brereton's horse to flight. A second charge was repelled by Gell's musketeers and Northampton was unhorsed. He refused to surrender and was killed.\n\n==Nighttime withdrawals==\nDuring the night the Royalists retired towards Stafford to regroup, and the Parliamentarian troops withdrew towards Chartley, leaving a large part of Gell's artillery in Royalist hands. Brereton withdrew to [[Nantwich]] while Gell marched through [[Uttoxeter]] to [[Derby]], taking Northampton's body with him. He attempted to ransom the Earl's body for the return of the captured artillery pieces, without success. The Royalists further refused a request to refund Gell for the cost of embalming their leader's body, which was then buried at All Hallows Church in Derby.\n\n==References==\n*Plant, David. [http://www.british-civil-wars.co.uk/military/1643-midlands.htm#hopton Hopton Heath, Staffordshire, 19 March 1643], on The British Civil Wars & Commonwealth website\n*Martyn Bennett, Spencer Compton, second earl of Northampton, Oxford DNB, 2004\n*English Heritage Battlefield Report: Hopton Heath 1643\n\n==External links==\n*''The Battle of Hopton Heath, 1643'': http://staffordshirehistories.co.uk/52612.html{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{coord|52.835|-2.067|type:event_region:GB-STS|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hopton Heath, Battle of}}\n[[Category:1643 in England]]\n[[Category:Battles of the English Civil Wars]]\n[[Category:Military history of Staffordshire|Battle of Hopton Heath]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1643]]\n[[Category:Registered historic battlefields in England]]\n[[Category:17th century in Staffordshire|Battle of Hopton Heath]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Battle of Hopton Heath\n| partof      = the [[First English Civil War]]\n| date        = 19 March 1643\n| place       = [[Hopton, Staffordshire|Hopton]], [[Staffordshire]]\n| image       = Battle of Hopton Heath.png\n| image_size  = 250px\n| caption     = ''The Battle of Hopton Heath'', engraved by J. T. Willmore after [[George Cattermole]]\n| result      = Both sides claimed victory\n| combatant1  = {{flagicon image|Royal Standard of England (1603\u20131689).svg|size=22px}} [[Cavalier|Royalists]]\n| combatant2  = [[File:Flag_of_England.svg|22px]] [[Roundhead|Parliamentarians]]\n| commander1  = [[Spencer Compton, 2nd Earl of Northampton]] {{KIA}}\n| commander2  = [[Sir John Gell, 1st Baronet]],<br>\n[[Sir William Brereton, 1st Baronet]]\n| strength1   = '''1,200:''' <br>1,100 cavalry, <br>100 infantry, <br> artillery\n| strength2   = '''1,500:''' <br> infantry, <br> cavalry, <br>15 pieces of artillery\n}}\n{{Campaignbox First English Civil War}}\nThe '''Battle of Hopton Heath''', in [[Staffordshire]], was a battle of the [[First English Civil War]], fought on Sunday 19 March 1643 between [[Roundhead|Parliamentarian]] forces led by [[Sir John Gell, 1st Baronet]] and [[Sir William Brereton, 1st Baronet|Sir William Brereton]] and a [[Cavalier|Royalist]] force under [[Spencer Compton, 2nd Earl of Northampton]]. The battle ended at nightfall, with the victory remaining a matter of opinion: that the Parliamentarian foot were still in position at nightfall when, as the Royalists themselves admitted, they drew back a little; or that next morning the Royalists occupied the field after the Parliamentarians retreated in the night. The Royalists had captured eight guns, but the Parliamentarians considered their killing of the enemy commander, the Earl of Northampton, of equal significance.\n\n==Background==\nGell had successfully taken the town of [[Lichfield]] in Staffordshire and was on his way with about 1,500 men and some [[artillery]] pieces to join Brereton in a projected attack on the town of [[Stafford]].\n\n==Battle==\nThey met at [[Hopton, Staffordshire|Hopton Heath]] and were attacked there by the Royalists, whose force consisted of about 1,100 cavalry, 100 foot and artillery, including a large artillery piece called Roaring Meg - which must not be confused with the siege mortar \"[[Roaring Meg (cannon)|Roaring Meg]]\" which was cast in 1646 for the siege of Goodrich Castle.\n\nAfter an artillery barrage the Royalist cavalry charged the entrenched Parliamentarians, putting Gell's [[dragoons]] and his and Brereton's horse to flight. A second charge was repelled by Gell's musketeers and Northampton was unhorsed. He refused to surrender and was killed.\n\n==Nighttime withdrawals==\nDuring the night the Royalists retired towards Stafford to regroup, and the Parliamentarian troops withdrew towards Chartley, leaving a large part of Gell's artillery in Royalist hands. Brereton withdrew to [[Nantwich]] while Gell marched through [[Uttoxeter]] to [[Derby]], taking Northampton's body with him. He attempted to ransom the Earl's body for the return of the captured artillery pieces, without success. The Royalists further refused a request to refund Gell for the cost of embalming their leader's body, which was then buried at All Hallows Church in Derby.\n\n==References==\n*Plant, David. [http://www.british-civil-wars.co.uk/military/1643-midlands.htm#hopton Hopton Heath, Staffordshire, 19 March 1643], on The British Civil Wars & Commonwealth website\n*Martyn Bennett, Spencer Compton, second earl of Northampton, Oxford DNB, 2004\n*English Heritage Battlefield Report: Hopton Heath 1643\n\n==External links==\n*''The Battle of Hopton Heath, 1643'': http://staffordshirehistories.co.uk/52612.html{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{coord|52.835|-2.067|type:event_region:GB-STS|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hopton Heath, Battle of}}\n[[Category:1643 in England]]\n[[Category:Battles of the English Civil Wars]]\n[[Category:Military history of Staffordshire|Battle of Hopton Heath]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1643]]\n[[Category:Registered historic battlefields in England]]\n[[Category:17th century in Staffordshire|Battle of Hopton Heath]]\n", "name_user": "VFF0347", "label": "safe", "comment": "Collapsed the table of battles.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Hopton_Heath"}
{"title_page": "1966 Pulitzer Prize", "text_new": "[[File:You Mean You Were Bluffing?.jpg|thumb|The prize-winning cartoon, \"You Mean You Were Bluffing?\"]]\n[[File:Flee to Safety.jpg|thumb|\"Flee to Safety\", cited as an exemplary work by the prize-winning photographer]]\nThe following are the '''[[Pulitzer Prize]]s''' for 1966.\n\n==Journalism awards==\n\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for Public Service|Public Service]]:\n** ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', for its campaign to prevent confirmation of Francis X Morrissey as a Federal District Judge in Massachusetts.\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for local General or Spot News Reporting|Local General or Spot News Reporting]]:\n** Staff of ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'', for its coverage of the [[Watts Riots]].\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for Investigative Reporting|Local Investigative Specialized Reporting]]:\n** [[John Anthony Frasca]] of ''[[The Tampa Tribune]]'', for his investigation and reporting of two robberies that resulted in the freeing of an innocent man.\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for National Reporting|National Reporting]]:\n** [[Haynes Johnson]] of the ''[[Washington Star|Washington Evening Star]]'', for his distinguished coverage of the civil rights conflict centered about [[Selma, Alabama]], and particularly his reporting of its aftermath.\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for International Reporting|International Reporting]]:\n** [[Peter Arnett]] of [[Associated Press]], for his coverage of the war in [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]].\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for Editorial Writing|Editorial Writing]]:\n** [[Robert Lasch]] of the ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]'', for his distinguished editorial writing in 1965.\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for Editorial Cartooning|Editorial Cartooning]]:\n** [[Don Wright (cartoonist)|Don Wright]] of ''[[The Miami News]]'', for \"You Mean You Were Bluffing?\"\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for Photography|Photography]]:\n** [[Kyoichi Sawada]] of [[United Press International]], for his combat photography of the war in Vietnam during 1965. A photo entitled \"Flee to Safety\", depicting a Vietnamese family wading across a river after their village was attacked, was cited as a noted example of his work.<ref>{{cite news|title=Boston newspaper wins Pulitzer Prize|work=Quad-City Times|location=Davenport, Iowa|agency=AP|date=May 3, 1966|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48564932/boston-newspaper-wins-pulitzer-prize/|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\n==Letters, Drama and Music Awards==\n\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for Fiction|Fiction]]:\n** ''Collected Stories'' by [[Katherine Anne Porter]] ([[Harcourt (publisher)|Harcourt]]).\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for Drama|Drama]]:\n**No award given.\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for History|History]]:\n** ''The Life of the Mind in America'' by [[Perry Miller]] ([[Harcourt (publisher)|Harcourt]]).\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for Biography or Autobiography|Biography or Autobiography]]:\n** ''A Thousand Days'' by [[Arthur Schlesinger, Jr.]] ([[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|Houghton]]).\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for Poetry|Poetry]]:\n** ''Selected Poems'' by [[Richard Eberhart]] ([[New Directions Publishing|New Directions]]).\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for General Non-Fiction|General Non-Fiction]]:\n** ''[[Wandering Through Winter]]'' by [[Edwin Way Teale]] ([[Dodd, Mead and Company|Dodd]]).\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for Music|Music]]:\n** ''Variations for Orchestra'' by [[Leslie Bassett]] ([[Edition Peters|Peters]])<br>It was first performed in the United States by [[Eugene Ormandy]] and the [[Philadelphia Orchestra]] at the Academy of Music in Philadelphia on October 22, 1965.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.pulitzer.org/awards/1966}}\n\n{{Pulitzer Prize}}\n\n[[Category:Pulitzer Prizes by year]]\n[[Category:1966 awards|Pulitzer Prize]]\n[[Category:1966 in the United States|Pulitzer Prize]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:You Mean You Were Bluffing?.jpg|thumb|The prize-winning cartoon, \"You Mean You Were Bluffing?\"]]\n[[File:Flee to Safety.jpg|thumb|\"Flee to Safety\", cited as an exemplary work by the prize-winning photographer]]\nThe following are the '''[[Pulitzer Prize]]s''' for 1966.\n\n==Journalism awards==\n\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for Public Service|Public Service]]:\n** ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', for its campaign to prevent confirmation of Francis X Morrissey as a Federal District Judge in Massachusetts.\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for local General or Spot News Reporting|Local General or Spot News Reporting]]:\n** Staff of ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'', for its coverage of the [[Watts Riots]].\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for Investigative Reporting|Local Investigative Specialized Reporting]]:\n** [[John Anthony Frasca]] of ''[[The Tampa Tribune]]'', for his investigation and reporting of two robberies that resulted in the freeing of an innocent man.\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for National Reporting|National Reporting]]:\n** [[Haynes Johnson]] of the ''[[Washington Star|Washington Evening Star]]'', for his distinguished coverage of the civil rights conflict centered about [[Selma, Alabama]], and particularly his reporting of its aftermath.\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for International Reporting|International Reporting]]:\n** [[Peter Arnett]] of [[Associated Press]], for his coverage of the war in [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]].\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for Editorial Writing|Editorial Writing]]:\n** [[Robert Lasch]] of the ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]'', for his distinguished editorial writing in 1965.\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for Editorial Cartooning|Editorial Cartooning]]:\n** [[Don Wright (cartoonist)|Don Wright]] of ''[[The Miami News]]'', for \"You Mean You Were Bluffing?\"\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for Photography|Photography]]:\n** [[Kyoichi Sawada]] of [[United Press International]], for his combat photography of the war in Vietnam during 1965. A photo entitled \"Flee to Safety\", depicting a Vietnamese family wading across a river after their village was attacked, was cited as a noted example of his work.<ref>{{cite news|title=Boston newspaper wins Pulitzer Prize|work=Quad-City Times|location=Davenport, Iowa|agency=AP|date